He lied, bribed, bargained, bullshitted, did anything to survive. He wrote a bunch of letters to Stalin talking about how much he loved Marxism and asking for asylum. When they left him for dead and shipped him to China he pretended to have gone crazy, gave bribes to officials.

The fact that Emperor Puyi (actually his friends called him "Henry") is actually remembered as a naive and clumsy idiot instead of a cold-blooded, ruthless and cunning aristocrat who managed to survive through multiple worst case scenarios just proves how well he played his role.

Back in China he immediately started screaming about how horrible monarchy was, reporting close relatives as reactionary. In the end not only did he survive, they made his brother member of the Presidium. It's like if Romanov was alive and the Tsarevich was in the Supreme Soviet.

A few years before his death he became a member of the "Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference". He died very early of cancer but if he lived into his 80s he was probably going to end up occupying high political positions like his brother.

NangaParbat1618 had a few posts on how G. W. Crile thought feet are ticklish as an adaptation to walking on rough terrain. Becoming ticklish replaces pain with ticklishness and this makes feet resistant to trauma. Humor and laughter are like this too I think, they replace fear.

There is an anecdote in Arthur Jones' biography where he and one of his friends crashed an airplane, went through 6 utility poles, totally trashed the plane, but somehow both survived and were ok. They couldn't stop laughing for hours. He said it was a release of nervous energy.

Anecdotally when me and one of my frens crashed a BMW drifting we did laugh a ton in the ambulance afterwards. Releases the nervous tension. All laughter is the devil's laughter - but in this world it's still better to be ticklish and laugh than to feel pain and fear. Resilience.
